The Telegraph - Calcutta : Nation
		 Friday, January 02, 2004 				 Jaya nod to global B-School 
 OUR SPECIAL CORRESPONDENT																								Chennai, Jan. 1: Tamil Nadu chief minister Jayalalithaa began the new year by promising support for a B-School that will boast a galaxy of global business leaders in its academic advisory council.																								Jayalalithaa assured Professor Bala V. Balachandran, the J.L. Kellogg Distinguished Professor of Management of the North Western University, Evanston, US, at a meeting at the secretariat here today that her government would back all efforts to establish the school by April.																								Balachandran told her that the school will be named The Great Lakes Institute of Management, Chennai, and explained details of the project plan drawn up for establishing the school.																								Management gurus like C.K. Prahlad of the University of Michigan, Phil Kotler of Kellogg, Seenu Srinivasan of the Stanford University, Krishna Ramaswamy of the Wharton School of Management and Kasha Rangan of Harvard will be part of the schools academic council, Balachandran told the chief minister.																								Balachandran said his aim was to establish a business school in Chennai on sound lines so that cost-effective management education is made possible. The chief minister, in turn, promised full support, saying the school will help strengthen Chennais position as a global manufacturing hub and business capital.																								Jayalalithaa had another surprise visitor at the secretariat NRI businessman from London Lord Swraj Paul, who congratulated her for the all round progress achieved by Tamil Nadu under her dynamic leadership.																								Britains business ambassador showed particular interest in the growth of the tourism and recreation industry in the state as well as in the fashion industry. 																								Tamil Nadu chief secretary Lakshmi Pranesh and finance secretary . Narayanan were among the top officials who were present at both the meetings.
